defaultDr Tim Brown and his colleagues have been involved in
default consultancy and research projects on improving customer services for over 15 years. Their focus has been on housing, planning and regeneration including:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultDr Brown previously submitted writ
defaultten material and gave oral evidence to the Public Administration Select Committee Inquiry into choice, voice and public services in 2004/05.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe long term reform of public services focuses on choice, empowerment and personalisation for individuals and communities. The benefits centre on capacity building as well as outcomes. However, it is a time-consuming and resource intensive process to deve
defaultlop local innovative approaches to service delivery. There is, thus, a danger that radical models will remain at the margins rather than becoming part of the mainstream. One of the ways of addressing this challenge is to learn the lessons from other countr
defaulties.  
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultTo what extent is the Government’s public service reform 
defaultprogramme
defaultsucceeding in:
defaulta. Empowering citizens?
defaultb. Improving public services?
defaultc. Ensuring that public services are accountable to the people
defaultwho use them, and to elected 
defaultofficials?
default&#xa0;
defaultThe current Government’s 
defaultprogramme
default is a continuation of the work of previous administrations on putting the customer first in the design and delivery of public services. It represents a positive shift from the paternalistic ‘professionals know 
defaultbest’ approach. The principles of empowerment, choice and 
defaultpersonalisation
default are the three key elements of a long term consensus that is also apparent in many other Western European countries. For the purpose of clarity, ‘empowerment’ relates to the provision
default of information so that the 
defaultuser has the knowledge of what is on offer, by whom and how. ‘Choice’ 
defaultcentres
default on the opportunities for users to choose the content and level of service, the provider and form of access. ‘
defaultPersonalisation
default’  refers to the ability o
defaultf the user to actively make informed decisions
default. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAs public service reform is a long term project, it is difficult to evaluate the impact of the current government’s policies. Major changes take a long time to design and implement. For example, the previo
defaultus administration’s target set in 2002 that 100% of councils and their partners should be using choice-based lettings in social housing by the end of 2010 was achieved, as less than 5% failed to meet this requirement. In relation to community land trusts, 
defaultthe previous Government’s Green Paper on Housing in 2007 
defaultemphasised
default their role. This has been further strengthened by this Government in its housing strategy in November 2011. In research that we undertook in 2012, we concluded that there was considerable 
defaultinterest with over 150 active 
defaultorganisations
default. But outcomes in terms of new affordable homes and community-owned and managed facilities were limited. For example, less than 100 homes had so far been completed (see below). This was mainly because of the time 
defaultrequired by communities to build up their skills and to go through the development process, which can be between 3-5 years.       
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultWhat evidence is there that citizen-
defaultcentred
default approaches to public
defaultservice design, delivery and choice of provi
defaultder can deliver better
defaultoutcomes—ensuring not only better value for money, but also
defaultgreater social, economic and environmental value?
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultIn relation to community land trusts (CLTs) and similar initiatives, progress on
default the development of specific projects since the Quirk Review on community asset disposals in 2007 has been slow. In a study of CLTs in 2012, we found that although there were over 150 active 
defaultorganisations
default, less than 100 affordable homes had been completed.
default Nevertheless a re-occurring theme from this and earlier research highlighted the benefits to communities and individuals in building up capacity, confidence, skills and trust. For example, 
defaultthe development of a small CLT in 
defaultCumbria
default contributed to the abili
defaultty of the local community to take over the ownership and management of the village pub, thus saving it from closure.  
default&#xa0;
defaultWe would conclude that while outcomes are vital, one should not ignore the benefits of the process for communities and individuals. 
